BACKGROUND AND NEED FOR LEGISLATION
The International Boundary and Water Commission (IBWC or
Commission) was established in 1889 and is an international body
composed of the United States Section and the Mexican Section.
The IBWC is responsible for applying the boundary and water trea-
ties between the United States and Mexico. As part of this respon-
sibility, the IBWC undertakes a variety of infrastructure projects
to implement existing treaties and international agreements, as
well as to resolve new or emerging boundary or water problems.
The United States Section of the IBWC currently operates and
maintains roughly 100 hydrologic gaging stations, 500 miles of lev-
ees, 20,000 acres of floodplains, four diversion dams, two inter-
national storage dams and associated hydroelectric power plants,
more than 500 hydraulic structures, two international wastewater
treatment plants, and half of all boundary monuments and mark-
ers on the land boundary and at ports of entry.1 Additionally, the
IBWC conducts and reviews environmental impact studies, water
quality monitoring, hydraulic studies, and develops design plans for
construction and renovation of water infrastructure projects.2
H.R. 1948 authorizes the IBWC to accept funds from other Fed-
eral agencies and non-Federal partners to study, design, construct,
operate, and maintain water resource infrastructure. This legisla-
tion builds on the United States-Mexico-Canada Agreement Imple-
mentation Act (P.L. 116–113), which directed the United States En-
vironmental Protection Agency (EPA) to work with the IBWC to
address international transboundary water flows originating in
Mexico and appropriated $300 million to EPA for the purpose of
constructing and maintaining water infrastructure. This authority
was later amended in the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2023
(P.L. 117–328) to authorize the transfer of this funding from EPA
to the IBWC to carry out this work.
H.R. 1948 also aligns the IBWC’s authorities with other Federal
agencies that are authorized to receive funding from non-Federal
entities. For example, the United States Army Corps of Engineers
(Corps) is eligible to receive funding from non-Federal partners for
the study, design, construction, and operation and maintenance of
infrastructure projects.3
The Commissioner of the United States Section of the IBWC,
Maria-Elena Giner, testified before the Subcommittee on Water
and Environment of the Committee on Transportation and Infra-
structure during the 118th Congress. Commissioner Giner stated
that the IBWC has a $473 million deferred maintenance backlog
and that the ability to accept additional funding would allow the
